# Extract relevant address columns from all DataFrames for comparison
addresses_1 = df1[['Billing Address Line 1', 'Billing City', 'Billing State/Province', 'Billing Zip/Postal Code']].dropna()
addresses_2 = df2[[df2.columns[1], df2.columns[2], df2.columns[3]]].dropna()
addresses_2.columns = ['Address', 'City', 'State']
addresses_3 = df3[[df3.columns[1], df3.columns[2], df3.columns[3]]].dropna()
addresses_3.columns = ['Address', 'City', 'State']

# Combine the Lumina Solar leads
addresses_2['Source'] = 'Baltimore List'
addresses_3['Source'] = 'Washington List'
addresses_combined = pd.concat([addresses_2, addresses_3], ignore_index=True)

# Normalize the formatting to improve cross-referencing
addresses_1['Full Address'] = addresses_1.apply(
    lambda x: f"{x['Billing Address Line 1']}, {x['Billing City']}, {x['Billing State/Province']} {x['Billing Zip/Postal Code']}".strip().lower(), axis=1)
addresses_combined['Full Address'] = addresses_combined.apply(
    lambda x: f"{x['Address']}, {x['City']}, {x['State']}".strip().lower(), axis=1)

# Cross-reference to find common addresses
common_addresses = addresses_1[addresses_1['Full Address'].isin(addresses_combined['Full Address'])]

import ace_tools as tools; tools.display_dataframe_to_user(name="Common Addresses in Both Lists", dataframe=common_addresses)
